</div></div><div id="text-13" class="widget widget_text"><div class="widget-wrap"><h3 class="widgettitle"><span>GIS Book Pick</span></h3>	<div class="textwidget"> <p><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/158948262X?ie=UTF8&tag=gislounge-20&linkCode=as2&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=158948262X"><img pagespeed_lazy_src="http://1-ps.googleusercontent.com/h/www.gislounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/85x100xlookofmaps.jpg.pagespeed.ic.FVMwDjB7P7.webp" style="border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-width: 0px; margin: 10px;" width="85" height="100" align="left" src="//1-ps.googleusercontent.com/h/www.gstatic.com/psa/static/1.gif" onload="pagespeed.lazyLoadImages.loadIfVisible(this);"></a><em><strong><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/158948262X?ie=UTF8&tag=gislounge-20&linkCode=as2&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=158948262X">The Look of Maps: An Examination of Cartographic Design</a></strong></em> is a cartographic classic by Arthur H. Robinson originally published in 1952. The book was based on Robinsons doctoral research which investigated the relationship between science and art in cartography and the resultant refinement of graphic techniques in mapmaking to present dynamic geographic information.</p> </div>
